data.text:
IRELAND'S UNDER 20s seek to close out the pool stages of the Rugby World Championships with a 100% record this afternoon.

So far Willie Faloon's side have racked up wins against Georgia and Italy to already all but secure their passage to the semi-finals.

Here's everything to know about to catch their final group outing:

What Irish TV channel is Ireland Under 20s vs Australia on?

It won't be televised anywhere, however, you can stream it on rugbypass.com.

It's free too. All you need to do is set up an account with them.

What Irish time is kick-off?

It will get going at 1 pm our time.

Surprisingly there's only an hour's time difference between ourselves and South Africa.

What is the Ireland starting team?

Faloon has made a whopping 12 changes in total as he aims to give everyone significant minutes over the course of the tournament.

Backs: Ben O’Connor (UCC RFC/Munster), Finn Treacy (Galwegians RFC/Connacht), Wilhelm de Klerk (UCD RFC/Leinster), Hugh Gavin (Galwegians RFC/Connacht), Hugo McLaughlin (Lansdowne FC/Leinster), Jack Murphy (Clontarf FC/Leinster), Oliver Coffey (Blackrock College RFC/Leinster)

Forwards: Emmet Calvey (Shannon RFC/Munster), Danny Sheahan (Cork Constitution FC/Munster), Patreece Bell (Sale Sharks/IQ Rugby), Alan Spicer (UCD RFC/Leinster), Billy Corrigan (Old Wesley RFC/Leinster), James McKillop (Queen’s University Belfast RFC/Ulster), Bryn Ward (Ballynahinch RFC/Ulster), Brian Gleeson (Garryowen FC/Munster)(captain),

Replacements: Stephen Smyth (Old Wesley RFC/Leinster), Jacob Boyd (Queen’s University Belfast RFC/Ulster), Andrew Sparrow (UCD RFC/Leinster), Sean Edogbo (UCC RFC/Munster), Max Flynn (Galway Corinthians RFC/Connacht), Tadhg Brophy (Naas RFC/Leinster), Sean Naughton (Galway Corinthians RFC/Connacht), Davy Colbert (Dublin University FC/Leinster).
